<TITLE> `Complex laws deprive women of land rights` </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 23 (bdnews24.com)  Women must be given greater land rights for real empowerment, while legal complexities are depriving some women of the few they have, speakers at a seminar said on Saturday. The speakers on women's empowerment agreed that without such empowerment of women, genuine development across the country would continue to be impeded. Organised by the Association of Development Agencies of Bangladesh, at the National Press Club in Dhaka on Saturday, the seminar aired the need for amendment of existing laws. Regarding legal complexities, it heard that existing laws make it complicated for widows to apply for khas lands, for example. MP Benazir Ahmed, member of the parliamentary standing committee on land, said the present government is working to ensure the rights of women and sought everyone's assistance for that. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina is working hard to establish women's rights in the country, he said. Benazir said that it was very reasonable to distribute khas, or public, land among the poor. He also said: "No slums will be evicted from government lands without rehabilitation in future." The MP said he would ensure that the rights of slum-dwellers, including those in his Dhaka constituency, are upheld. The parliamentary committee would take steps so that women's right are ensured in this, he said. But, he added: "There are swindlers among women too. They are working with organised gangs. They will have to be freed from these influences." The seminar was presided over by ADAB president Abdul Mati
